column1314:
The International Human Rights Foundation (IHRF) strongly condemns the vicious persecution of independent journalists living in exile abroad by the authoritarian state of Pakistan. It is a well-known fact that independent journalists cannot voice dissent against the military-led regime in Pakistan. The country has already incarcerated thousands of political workers, including former Prime Minister Imran Khan. The recent elections were marred by allegations of manipulation and significant irregularities reported to keep Imran Khan's party out of power. Under these circumstances, the only realistic reporting and investigative journalism challenging this authoritarianism in Pakistan is being conducted by a few brave individuals working as independent journalists while living abroad, some in exile, facing threats to their lives and livelihoods.

In the case of IHRF's permanent representative for Pakistan, Adil Raja (@soldierspeaks), who is working as an independent journalist based in the UK, he faced threats to his life by Pakistan's intelligence agency ISI, SLAPP (Strategic Lawsuit Against Public Participation) legislation by an ISI official in the UK, persecution of his family in Pakistan, and allegations of incitement to violence in Pakistan, for which he was cleared by the UK's counterterrorism authorities after a detailed investigation.

In a series of fictitious cases in Pakistan, a court yesterday ordered the seizure of properties and the blocking of national IDs and passports of independent journalists Adil Raja, Dr. Moeed Pirzada, Shaheen Sehbai, Syed Haider Mehdi, Sabir Shakir, and Wajahat Saeed Khan, rendering some stateless in contradiction to Article 15 of the Universal Declaration of Human Rights. These actions by the state of Pakistan speak volumes about the curbs on freedom of expression and the crackdown on journalistic freedoms. The IHRF overwhelmingly condemns this shameless persecution of these journalists and activists and calls for the intervention by international human rights bodies to hold Pakistani State accountable for this politically motivated persecution.
